\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Did your mother or father ever read to you when you were young?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 No. No. Prety - I was pretty good at - good at school you know. They all said I was. And I got on, you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Did they read bedtime books to you or something like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 No, they never - never done no reading to me, she never did - never got no time I don't think she ever had any time those days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Were there any newspapers or anything like that around?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 
Oh - oh I was - we weren't allowed to read newspapers. Wouldn't let us read papers, that - 'course I used to always try to wangle one somehow somewhere to have a read, and I - as I say, when I was having my first baby I never knew not
hing about it, you know, and - and - and I went to a friend and my - I didn't like to approach her. Tell you how silly I was. And I was having me first baby and didn't know where it come from even. And I went to a friend of mine and I said to her - I expl
a
ined to her and I said, I do feel silly, and I - I said, I don't - can't talk to my George about it. And - that's me husband, but I couldn't talk to him about it, and she said - well, she said, you listen here, she said, I tell you, where you have it in i
t
 - it'll come out that's all there is about it and I'm not telling you no more. And I blushed, went pink you know, and I - said, that's a fine way, she said, well I've never had no children but that's all I know. I - I'm telling you the straight way - str
a
ightforward way, and she said, buck up and go and ask your mother. And I say to my mum really was to - she looked after - she was a good old - good - midwife she was but she didn't carry it right out you know. And she used to do all the mother's round whe
r
e we lived, everybody thought the - anything was wrong they'd always send for her you know. And when she - I was going to be confined, I said, what's going to happen I can't have it? She said, never mind about what you can't have, you've got to have. And 
y
ou've got a long way to go yet so it's no good you worrying, she said to my old man, you bugger off somewhere George, she said, and come back later on. And I remember were were - we was roughed up at the time because - my George was out of work, and he's 
o
ut of work and this morning he was - Plesseys like a big firm like this they was going that day, they built the Midland Bank up at - he got this job on the Midland Bank, right up - near Bishopsgate somewhere it was, and - I know he didn't come home 'til t
w
elve o'clock at night and I was lonely. Yes, a long way away. And there was a - and I was worrying about him, and of course when he came in he - oh he'd cut his arm up here, and - he'd only just started, been out of work about three months, and we weren't
 
half hard up, I tell you - I went and pawned the blooming iron, so I know what it is to go through rough times. You know, we never got no maternity benefit then we had to pay - when you had a baby or that then you had to pay for everything yourself. All o
ut your husband's money. Cost you - three pound ten I paid, I had a Scotc}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16659317\charrsid1641457 h}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 
 doctor, and used to have to put so much away a week out the wages to pay the - do you know the - look at the money they get today. My daughter got twenty-four pound. And I said to he
r, well how do you get all that money? Blimey, I said I was born a bit late in life, I should have been born a bit early for this. And she said, well that's the money you get mum. I said, well - I said, of course I said I know what you get now, but I said
 
in our days there was no free milk or nothing like that. And I remember when my father was ill - when you - my - my mother went to the bun house to help to - you know, 'cos she didn't enough money then to buy - to buy him a few necessaries. He got - died 
of a liver complain my father did, some - I don't know exactly what it was.
