\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Did women go into pubs in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 No. Not much, no, no. No. 
No, there's no - you know, the old girl have a party, we'd have - all have a good time but - wasn't - wouldn't be a lot of drink about, flying about.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Before 1918 when you were still at school what kind of things would you do at Christmas together?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 
Oh - well - at - at Christmas we'd - you know, get the Christmas tree and - all - all have our pocket money, we always used to get so much, a bit of money each week when the old girl treat us, you know, if we'd behaved ourselves for our jobs all the wee
k, and then we'd all buy bits and she'd buy bits and pieces, and she'd put all the chains up you know. It was a real right do you know, we never went short of nothing, you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 What would you eat for Christmas dinner?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Ay? Oh - oh - lump of beef
 and she'd kill chick - kill - kill a chicken and we'd generally had a aitch bone of beef. Of course the meat that days was delicious. Aitch bone of beef you could slice off you know. Today they're about - want about two pound twelve for one of them, you 
don't very often see them. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Did you play games and things like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 
Oh play - yes, play, mm, oh yes - postman's knock and all that business. As a matter of fact when my brother bought - his mate home from the army - he - he \{ILLEGIBLE\} in the
 army and he - he came home, we played postman's knock, and of course the thought that - I was going to marry his mate and they thought I - oh I used to thought I was well away, but I've often - I didn't tell anybody, I'd already met my husband and I was 
c
ourting him but nobody knew. And I used to play the piano, and this bloke used to - make - he used to sing you know, and then - mum - my mother said to me one day, you're - two are getting very thick. I said, oh yes. That's all right. And then I said no m
o
re, I said old Dick's all right, I said, but I don't think I'd like him as a husband. And she said - what do you mean? I - wall - that's all right, and one day he said to me will you - like to come to theatre or something, Victoria Palace, I said, no, I'm
 
meeting my young man. And he said, oh, I never knew nothing about this. I - oh well, I don't tell everybody what I'm doing of. And - and he married my sister in the finish, he turned out a good husband though. They only had one - one - boy. Two - two boys
 they had, yes, two.
\par 
