\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 
Oh yes, and - but my mum never used to sub any money, she used to - she was one of the lucky ones, but I've seen - I - I was only a kid but I remember
 some of the mothers coming home without any money 'cos - they sort of lived - had to live on it. But my mum was luckier than some you know. She never had to sub any money. She used to - wait 'til the end of the - 'til we finished and then the old farmer 
w
ould - we'd all go in the cart you know, in the old cart them days, with a great big old horse, and - would take us to the station. Else some of us would - my mum used to take a pushchair with all her - we had to take all your linen down and things, cups 
a
nd saucers and - everything you wanted to use, they didn't supply - the farmer didn't supply anything like that, but they were very kind to the people like my sister - had this face ache, it was very bad, you couldn't get a doctor anywhere down there, tha
t
 was the only snag about it, if - if you had to have a doctor - the farmer got a doctor - was miles away, well you had to wait for him and all that but - she had this face very bad and this farmer's wife I remember today as if it was - quite clear to me, 
s
he - hadn't been asleep for about two nights, she was only about - seven, wasn't very old, and - this farmer made her - I've often thought of it as I've got older too - brown paper, with vinegar and pepper on, and mixed it all in a paste and just - made o
n
e blob and put it on her face. Anyhow it done her good whatever it was. And she went - it went down and she got off to sleep with it afterwards. But it was the only thing as I say - when it's wet you can't go on the fields, you'd be up to your neck - neck
 
in mud, you couldn't do - there was no work done and it was - really the weather was really bad. I went right - years - my boy was only a baby, and I went on me own with somebody - and - well he's forty-seven now me eldest son and I took him down as a bab
y
, but my husband - the weather was so rough my husband came down and took me home. He wouldn't let me stop, he said, you're not fit to be - I said, where have you come from? He said, get your stuff packed up, we're going home. I said, what for? He said, y
ou'll get - blooming get your death of cold down here. He said, you can't live for - I used to like it, it was holiday you see, and I - I didn't mind going with these friends and - my mum didn't go any more.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Did you work on Saturdays and Sundays there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 
Oh yes, down there, yes. Yes, you had to work all the time and you had to do your share too. And I mean a bloke would come round and - pull the poles out for you, if you - there was anywhere - anyone about when they had the pole hops, but - honestl
y when you - sort of get up into the field and see masses and masses of - hops - growing, it drive you a bit silly to look at 'em all, you think how the hell you're going to - 'course they used to time - the farmers would time how many - how many days tha
t
 would take to clear that field, and you couldn't go in to another field 'til that was all clear. And - you know, they had a certain night for pole - you see, they used to have - I suppose what I thought was they used to do so many pole hops, and so many 
-
 what they call the vine hops, but that was on the strings, but I think they - did a test to see which one were the best one out the two. Sometimes the vine hops would be better than the pole hops, it was all according where you was. 'Cos if you got - the
 
- great big hops like you used to have sometimes, it wouldn't take half so many to get a barrel full. But I mean if you got some little ones it took you - a long time to pick 'em - a good few. 'Cos my mother keep - used to keep you at it you know, no runn
ing around. And 'course you had to - they were supposed to take - it was proper high - the kids all used to enjoy it any rate, you know, make a real right holiday of it you know.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 A long one as well wasn't it, eight weeks?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Yes, yes, eight weeks. 
Oh it was always a recognised thing when I was a kid, hopping was always - if I'd been a - at school, you know, my mum's gone, took the other - the other two, my two sisters younger than me, and I haven't gone, my father - I said, oh I'll stop with dad an
d
 I'd look after him, make him a cup of tea - perhaps I've only been - been at home about a - they've been gone perhaps a fortnight and I've missed 'em you know, and my dad said, go on, off, get yourself ready, here's your fare, go down to your mother, I k
n
ow you want to go down there with her, you know, naturally, and 'course I've gone down and ended up with 'em but - as I say, when - when my boy was born I said to my husband, can I go, I said and he said, well I don't like the idea of you taking the baby.
 I said, well, I'd like to go, I said, I can't afford a holiday so -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Was it mainly women down there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 
No - women and - and their husbands. Yes, and they used to pack up their work some of the husbands did to go with their wives 'cos there was the 
money, used be some lovely money earned at it, and a lot of them did, you know, I knew - women and their wives - husbands used to go, take all the kids. And 'course it was a holiday for all the lot of 'em. Oh dear.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Did you ever go to the seaside?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 
No, no, I don't think we ever went to seaside, no. I don't think there was ever any - well - mother always used to say she didn't have enough but - whether they ever did I don't know anything about that but I know I never went to seaside, but not - I don
't remember -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 You said something about the school holiday camps?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 
Oh - oh yes, I did go once to - what do they call the - Country holiday fund, you had to pay so much a week at school to go to them. And I - I used to sometimes have a - I think it
's about a fortnight - so many kids go you know in the school they - collect 'em up and then they all meet together and - and take a bit of - they all used to treat me, you know, my brothers, sisters and that, all those to had it, and dad used to treat me
 
and - I'd go off for about a fortnight and - we used to go - forget now where we used to go. Not very far away. But not seaside, used to be mostly country they would send you you know. 'Cos them day they thought the country was - better than seaside I sup
p
ose. They - they said about Southend, I've heard people say years ago that - it was a load of mud but wouldn't think it today - would you? What they've done. And they don't stand no nonsense down there with the - pop groups that get down there, if they pl
a
y up they always got the old - the old van there and cart 'em all off they do, they don't stand none of it today. That is much better than what it was years - years ago. I can remember, as I say, when it did used to be a proper rough hole. But not s- - no
t
 so bad now. 'Cos they made it like that and they're very strict down there as I say, they don't stand no nonsense with the - these that go in the pubs you know and they - and they say - down there they get the - the Black Mari standing by when they turn 
out the pubs down there so - so a friend of mine told me so that when they all came - they kick up rough they bunged 'em all in and - and shut 'em all - take 'em all to the station.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Was there much fighting or roughness round the area you lived in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 
No, it was - no - it was pretty quiet where we lived you know. 'Cos we - were allowed to - we had a big garden and my mother always kept us in the garden, we weren't allowed to run the streets you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Is this Tappersfield Road?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Tappersfield
 Road, yes, we had a big garden there, and we had a big garden but wasn't many where we lived, when we went to Meeting House Lane, Peckham, there wasn't many kids around there you know. Was a - sort of a - well - there wasn't no children, all the elderly 
p
eople sort of you know, going to retire and things like that. They say you didn't know that today so a friend of mine told me, she said, it's all down, it's all nothing else but blocks of flats. Funny, everywhere is altered today. You don't realize it. Oh
 
no. You know, I went up to the hospital some time ago to - and we went through Hammersmith, I didn't know where I was. I said to the - ambulance man, whereabouts is this? He said, you're in Hammersmith. I said, what, Hammersmith? I didn't dream, but they'
ve done it all the way round haven't they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 What would you do on Sundays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Sunday, oh well we went Sunday school. Went to church in the morning, and we used to go to Sunday school in the afternoon.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Would your parents go to church?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 And - no, they never - my - I never known my mum and dad go to church. But \{ILLEGIBLE\}
 you she all - she see that we did sort of thing you know. As I say, she - you know - the - I suppose like every other mother and father they tried to do them best but - my fat
her died when he was fifty-four. He'd never had a day's illness in his life so she was - we were sort - sort of left you know. But I don't think she was badly off you know, she - 'course she was getting on then, she - of course was was almost grown - we w
e
re nearly all grown up - all married bar my youngest sister. And then when I left them and went to live with my mother-in-law up at Brixton - she got married while I - when I moved away, and they went to live - live at Mitcham you see, so - I don't see mu
ch of the family now, all I - see is my sister that lived at Dulwich, she lost her husband - with a heart -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 What kind of church was it that you attended, was it Church of England?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Church of England, yes, we always went - we were always brought u
p Church of England. The whole lot of us were. Though my - eld - next to the eldest sister she went Catholic when she - got married, but - myself, I don't know, I don't I've lived in flats with Catholic people and I - sometimes I don't think much of 'em a
t
 all, they may be all right, well like everybody else there's good and bad. But when we lived at Battersea, I lived with a - a couple over me, they's one little boy, and - what I can't understand about Catholic people is this. They have a good old row and
 
they argue and row and then the next morning they get up and go to church and confess all their sins. I can't hardly see that's right, but they had one little boy, Patrick, he was in the war, in the 1939 war, and I can remember as a kid they used to row o
v
er this child, 'cos - he wanted him brought up in the Catholic faith and she wanted a Protestant - a Protestant, and - there they used to have a row and he used to knock her about, they had the flat over me at Battersea, and I used to say to my mother, I 
s
aid, here they go again, all over bloody religion I used to say to him. And then - Sunday mornings they would get up as if nothing had happened, be as nice as pie, and they'd go to church and come back and then they'd take the kid out and go round the par
k or somewhere like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 In those days was it very sort of neighbourly?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 
Oh - yes, it was very - more neighbourly. Neighbours are not the same like they were today. Well I remember when I had been ill you know with the kids you know, and the old 
man - my old man was in the Gas Company then, and when - when we lived in Fulham Road and - the flu, I remember it was very bad about and I just went to school this morning with a - my girl, and the boy, I took 'em to school and I just come back and I fel
t
 so ill, flopped on the bed. Do you know, the neighbour - my neighbour underneath, I had a pile of washing to do, I was going to do, I just felt dead to the world, she came up, took all my washing away, but people today don't do those sort of things today
. They don't come and do your work today like they did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 What about before the first world war?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 
Well they - yes, very good neighbours, yes, very good neighbours, anybody, if you wanted helping hand - they'd help you, but - 'course you see - though
 - as I say, it's another generation and people just think of theirself. I suppose in a you can't blame 'em, really, I mean you know - look at all you lot today, you youngsters, I mean, look at the - what you do. In my days there wasn't no things}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2642704\charrsid1641457  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 like - so
rt of like that - like that even. The tape recorders and things like that, and I mean - look at the position you youngsters hold, some of you. Wonderful posit - well none of that when I was a girl. There was prizes - if you kept school regular, my mother 
-
 but - no jobs for - that you - the youngsters get today. I mean they do get wonderful jobs today you must admit. And my boy my eldest son that's got the business, he used to work for the - when he came out the army, he worked for the - glass company, a b
ig glass }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2642704\charrsid1641457 \endash }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457  Clarke}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2642704\charrsid1641457 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 s I think it was, and him and his mate used to go to - well they used to have to get on the train, I forget now what it was - but they used to go by train to work I know. Since he started.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 He's got the shop in Tooting High Road?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 
Yes, in Tooting High Road. And they do all the glass and it - he's made a packet on it I'll tell you, he really has. He's - he's a - he's got a lovely house at Stonelea and I've never been there because - as I say, in my family I never push meself, if th
ey want me to go I wait to be asked, I don't never push meself forward, with any of 'em, but - we were out one - Sunday, somebody took me to Brighton, my youngest boy I think it was took me to Brighton this day and he said, shall we call in to see Ronald 
a
s we come back? And I said, no, I've had enough, I was a bit tired. I said, let's get home George. And he said to me next day, he - he range me up, he said, why didn't you call in mum to see the house? But the friend that came here said to me - he was tal
k
ing about him you know, he knew him and - known him from a kid, and he said, he's down well for himself hasn't he, he said. I said, yes he has. So he said - he said, have you been - he said, it's a gorgeous house he's got at Stonelea. I said, yes, I think
 
it is, I said, I've never been there. Well, he said, it's a wonderful house. But, he said, it's not a home. He said, not where Doreen is, Dorreen - is - a she wants it for is a - she's his wife, he says, a show piece he said. You're frightened to walk ins
ide, he said, she'd got - well one of these days I'll show you some pictures if I see you again.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Going back to before the first world war would you have different clothes to wear on a Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Yes, my mother - we always had - my sister - and me, a
nd my youngest sister, we was all dressed together, 'cos the other two - was courting and they was a lot older than us the other - the first two, two girls, the eldest girl and the next one down. But - yes, we always had Sunday clothes, Sunday dresses, an
d - when went to school our school clothes you know. Yes, oh yes, she always kept us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Would you play games on a Sunday?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Yes. We could play game - you know - rounders we used to play out in the back, you know, in the garden. But not out the front
. Oh no. And you know when I got married my mother wouldn't allow me to do any - any washing, you know that, you wasn't allowed to put your washing outside of a Sunday. And I - I remember saying to my mum, well, I've got the baby and I've got to do my nap
p
ies on a Sunday, it don't make any difference. I haven't got all them nappies. And she said well don't hang 'em out the front - out the back, I don't like washing on the line. And though I was her daughter and had this young baby, I wasn't allowed to put 
a
ny washing on the line. I had to dry it indoors. Not Sundays, never done a - but today you wash on the Sunday, everybody - I've done it - washed my - I've been to work all the week and I've come home and I've done all my washing on a Sunday, here. And got
 up early and got it all out the way, but not them days you weren't allowed to. Mothers didn't allow you to. And you had -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 You could only play games in the back garden?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 On the back garden, yes. 'Til it was time to come in you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 So they didn't think it was wrong to play on a Sunday as such?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 No, no, my mother - well my mother didn't think it was wrong. It was only - as I say, she - long as you played in the back garden.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Were there any Sunday school outings at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 No, I never remember any, don't remember outings, not like they get up today.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 What about Sunday school prizes and things like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Well - I didn't remember, not prizes, not like - not - not - not all that much, don't remember any prizes - just had the b
ook you know with a little text in \{ILLEGIBLE\} you - they stamped with a star and my mother used to want to see it when you come home, make sure you'd been you know, sort of -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 What kind of things would you do at Sunday school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Oh well they would
 read the stories from the Bible more than anything you know, and then tell you about - you know, about Jesus and all that, you had to listen to that you know sort of thing. But - that's all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Did you like Sunday school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Yes, I - I never used to 
- I never used to mind school either - either, but - daughter was a one, she was a - terrible for school, and funny thing she brought up - one girl and three boys and they've all hated the sight of it. Said, well they take after you, that's all, I said, '
cos you never blooming liked it.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Were you ever a member of the choir or anything like that at church?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Oh no. No. My boy - my son was, in the church, but not me, nothing of that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Or your sisters or brothers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 No. No. No. Nothing like that, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Were there any sort of activities organized by the church that you took part in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 No I can't - no, I can't remember anything.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Did they have anything like a temperance club?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 No. No, nothing like that, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Was grace said at meals in your family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 
Oh yes, yes, when my father was - very particular over knives and forks - that were put on the table, with the cutlery as he used to call it, and he always said grace, we all said grace with him and - and we all had our place at
 the table.; And woe betide you if you didn't sit up properly. You know, he's very particular about that, my mum and dad were you know, sitting at the table. So there you are.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Were you ever taught to say prayers at night or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 O
h yes, we always had to say our prayers at night. That's the last thing my mother and father used to say to you when you went to bed - goodnight, even when we were married she'd say, don't forget your prayers, always say that, you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Would you have family prayers all together?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 
No, not - no family prayers but she'd just said to you when you said - she'd say well come on, so and so, Georgie get to bed now it's time, it's school tomorrow, and - she'd say, just say goodnight - don't forget your prayers. That's all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 What would your parents do when they weren't working, how they would spend the rest of the time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Well -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Did they have much time on their hands?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Well, I never used to see my mum sitting about much, she was always so
rt of doing something. And dad, he - he used to be sitting in the chair you know reading a bit of paper - reading the paper or - used to like the - old tuppenny books - what they do - did they used to call them - cowboys and something - I don't - I forget
 what they called - tuppence each they were, and he used to sit - my dad used to sit and read them all the time. And I've got a sister-in-law used to - she used to read them too but I could never get on with the damned things, I never liked 'em.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Picture books are they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 
Picture books, they were pictures books, you know - paper, all paper what you got the newsagents. Tuppence they used to cost then, my sister-in-law would - give us a - if we went up to see her or up there to the house to see - she u
sed to live with my mother-in-law, before I went to move up there, and - if I went up there you know she'd give me a few for my dad to bring home and he used to sit and read them. But I never can remember seeing my mum read much. You know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 What kind of things would she be doing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 
Washing and things like that you know. She was very fussy she was, in her place you know, she was - she'd - always used to annoy me when I was a kid, on a Sunday she always used to be wanting to turn the place upside down
, and I used to say to her, look at her and say, oh it's Sunday today. Say, I don't care. You have to be kept clean, she used to say to me, I don't care - well you're going to Sunday school any rate this afternoon, so you'll be out the way, but - it's fun
ny they - you never - never see her - sitting around you know, can't ever remember her sitting around.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Did she ever go out very much to see other people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 No, she never used to go - she - my dad used to take her out as I say - on Derby Day, he use
d to take her out and she used to dress herself up, but - she'd only just go up the road shopping, she never - you never see her go much anywhere. They never did, I can't remember 'em - going out anywhere - much them days, they was nearly all indoors life
 you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 She wasn't a member of anything like a Women}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2642704\charrsid1641457 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 s Institute?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 What time did your father get home from work in the evenings?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Oh he was home about - about six o'clock, somewhere like that, and he used to work 'til - on Sa
turdays - he used to work 'til - about half past twelve of a Saturday. And he used to come in and - and my - we used to have our dinner, not - we never had - had no dinner of a Saturday, we used to have what they call a high tea, something later in the ev
e
ning, you know, an evening meal, that was the only day of the week, and then he'd - he'd go and have a drink, he used to go and have a drink, glass of ale, that's all he used to drink and - that was the only time that I think I can remember him going out,
 Saturday. He'd go out 'til - the pubs closed you know, and then he'd come home and - he'd sit in the armchair and have a sleep. But the old lady, she used to be - running round shopping and all this at the Saturday.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Would she go out for a drink, you told me about your grandma?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 
Yes, oh yes. Well that's when - well - well when we came away from Tappersfield Road and moved to Meeting House Lane - 'course grandmas wasn't quite so near, which was a jolly good job, but - she used to perhaps go with dad
 in the evening to have a drink but never stop out late she never, you know, she'd get back again. She used to think the world of her mother too.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Was your father a member of any clubs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 A - a Christmas club, yes, they used to - mum used to belong
 to that and this pub used to hold like a - a - what they call a loan club. Between the - just all them - people that went in there regular you know, and - they used to belong to that for - for - for Christmas time you know. To buy - 'cos Christmas was Ch
ristmas them days you know. Oh - was gorgeous time. Really was, I've never seen Christmases like they have today. My mother always - money always sort of come up, where it come from God knows, whether - whether she saved it I don't know but -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Were the pubs open on Christmas Day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 
No, they were closed Christmas Day. She used to put all the chains up and - and a great big aitch bone of beef and a great big leg of pork and - then the neighbours used to come in of a evening you know, in the - in the ev
ening time and - she'd go out in the kitchen and cut all these beautiful sandwiches and - bring 'em all in on a tray and - I'd play the piano and - you'd have a good old time you know. Oh yes. Oh my husband used to say, I used to say to him - my sister - 
well all help me, and - and presents, we used to get lovely presents Christmas you know. 'Course that never used to cost half the money that all \{ILLEGIBLE\}
 what - you know, the kids today have too much. My grandchildren have too much you know. Now - one - this little girl's six. And all these toys.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Did your father ever take part in any sports or anything like that?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 No. No, he was - always a bit queer you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Do you remember if your father belonged to any sort of savings clubs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 No, only - this - only Christmas club.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 He was never a member of anything like a sick club?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Oh no, no, nothing of that, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 How did you get on with your brothers and sisters?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Oh, used to get on with them not too bad but - I never sort of - 
I could always sort of - happier on me own, I never mixed much with my sisters and brothers you know. I always sort of - like when they were - the elder ones ever got married and I was - sort of at home I never used to - you know, go around much with 'em 
at all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 There were two older ones and two younger ones?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Mm. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 How much older were the older ones than you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Well - my eldest sister is - she's eighty - in her eighties today, so she's - she's -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 So they'd be big girls almost by the time you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 
Yes, yes, that's right, mm. And the other one is seventy-six, the other sister seventy-six. Then there's another one - and then there's - there was a brother that died. He was sixty odd. Seven - no, he just have been in his seve
nties. And then there was - there's me - as I say, I'm sixty-nine.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 There wasn't a brother or sister that you felt particularly close to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 No. No. None of them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Who would you play with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Oh we used to play with the two young - but never 
used to - all that much you know, sort of - I was a sort of a - used to - like me own company, you know, used to read a lot when I went to school when I started - learning I used to - to have books to read and you know.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 What kind of books would you like?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 
Well - like story books, you know - history and all that sort of thing I used to like. I do now, I like - biographies and anything like that you know, very interesting.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Would you play with neighbours very much?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Oh yes, neighbours children, yes. I always sort of got on with them better than I did with me own, kind of thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Why was that do you think?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Ay? Oh I don't know why it was, it was just that I - used to like - I used to play with a cousin a lot too that lived in - in -
 where did she live, she lived along Peckham - when we lived there, I used to play with a cousin, Lottie, used to play with her quite a lot, we used to go to the same school - 'til we fell out and had a row you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 What was that about?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 And - you know, at school, something she'd say and - go and tell the other girls and I used to chase her round the playground.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Where would you play, you say you played in the back garden on a Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Was there anywhere else you'd play?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 
No, my mother never let us out on a Sunday any rate, but we used to - you know, I nearly always played in the back garden, 'cos it was a big garden, and then nobody else could interfere with the kids you know, with us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 What kind of things would you play?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 
We used to play - like dressing up and all those sort of things. Being a nurse and all that and a doctor coming - at school and all that sort of business and - and - worked out - sort of - plays between you - yourselves, you know, make up one and
 all that sort of thing, I used - as I used to say I used to live in a - make believe world and I believe I used to them days when I was a kid. I always wanted to grow up and be a nurse.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Would you have a nurse's costume or just pretend you had one?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 
A nurse - no, no, oh no, a nurse's costume. When - when - when my - when I was the only one at home with my - other sister when we lived at Meeting house Lane and I was - going to work - they used to say - once somebody said to my mother one day, who'
s that young girl lodger. That's me. And we always see her come in certain times. I worked at the picture palace where I met my husband, and he came to work there you see, and mother said to me one day she said, you do try to be the madam don't you. That'
s
 why nobody don't think you belong to me. The way you go on, she said. You - I said, oh well, that's all right, the way I want to be that's all. But I always kept just to myself sort of thing, I did have a friend, I did have a girl friend I used to go out
 with. Have a real right time. Mother used - never used to know anything about that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Were you free to play with anyone you pleased?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Oh yes, yes. Oh yes, she didn't stop us if we - we - we wanted to play with anybody.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Did you belong to any organisations like youth clubs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 No, there wasn't any - not - not when I was girl}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2642704\charrsid1641457  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 there's none - none of them placed about.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Your parents didn't discourage you from playing with certain children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Oh no. No, I don't think so.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Were you allowed to get dirty when you played?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Oh she didn't sort of mind.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Did you have any hobbies and things when you were at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Only reading, that's all, only reading.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 You didn't have any pets or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 No. No. No, no real - oh my
 brother used to keep - rabbits, but me - we - I didn't have no pets, no, 'cos my mother kept, as I told you, she kept a blooming farmyard.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Did you ever help her with that, getting the eggs in and that sort of thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Oh yes, I - I - oh yes, and 
- she had - my brother had pigeons, and my - my mice he used to have. I used to get scared of the mice. I am today, I don't like mice at all.
