pence up in the gallery, and I went to go up in the gallery and I reme
mber I lost - I got a good hiding for that too, because I lost all me wages. And me - wasn't a lot but - I didn't realize, I didn't like to go home 'cos I - you know, she was - she's a bit of a tartar my mum was, and -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Did you have any pocket money to go to these things with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 
Oh yes. Oh no - oh yes, she used to give us a couple of bob you know, well two shillings went a long way them days, you could get a pennorth of toffee and get a great big pile of it, you know, even when you went to school y
ou could buy happorths of sweets.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Would she give it to you once a week?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 
Oh - oh - yes, she'd give us so much - oh - so much a - every week, you know, she'd give us a bit and then - if we done a - anything extra, exciting, well you might get a bit more see in the week. But - she wasn't too bad that way.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Did you tell me you went to some concerts?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 
Yes, and when my sister - was on the stage I used to go to the Central Hall and used to - Peckham, we used to call it the Central Hall and I us
ed to - go and - play for her, you know, then I packed it all up 'cos I was the only one who could, she used to sing - Haiawatha's \{BLANK\}
 I always remember that donkey's years ago, and 'course I - - I used to grin all the time I played with her because - 
oh - Hiawatha's melody, you know, she was a bit of a - she used to try to be, like when she married this chap, you couldn't help laughing at her, see - he's a - had a shop down our way and - she got - friends with him and - then he - sold the shop and wen
t
 on the buses, he was a busman. Anyhow, you'd have thought she was lady D'Muck, you never thought she belonged to the Jordan's family any rate. And same as when she - she married this chap and we - didn't see much of her at all after that because she - yo
u know, nobody was good enough for her ladyship as we - my mother used to call her, wonder how her ladyship's today getting on, she used to say.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 You say your mother wasn't all that keen on her going on the stage and things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 No. She wasn't, no, she never liked it. She never -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Why do you think that was?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 
Well - I'll tell you what, there wasn't - I don't think there was so much - and I can't remember crime being like it was today. Never nothing like that but - I don't think - well, I don't 
think my mother thought it was a life for her girl you know. 'Course I mean them days - it wasn't like it is today, you know, all the money, they never got a lot of money and my mother used to - had her learnt dancing, toe dancing, that cost her - the old
 
lady a bit of money, and 'course she didn't - went - went to Ireland I think it was, and told - somebody came and told my mother she was walking the streets and all this and - 'course - my father never interfered much with the kids - any of us at all, but
 
- he used to let mother run the children, and he said - oh and I heard my dad say to her this night, he said, you just go and bring her home at once. And - she brought her - she did go too, the next day, she travelled over there and brought her back the n
ext day any rate. And she said, that's the end of the stage, we won't have no more of that - business, but whether she ever - and I - I lost run of them, I didn't - when I got married I didn't -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Did she ever go on the stage again?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 No, I don't think she did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 When you left school did your life change very much, did you find you stayed out in the evenings more?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Oh yes, yes, when I got - when I left school I used to go out a bit more you know with my friend, we used to go - round the band 
- band, Peckham Rye, walk round the bandstand, find the boys you know, and - my mum'd say, you be home by a certain time and - what she said certain time you just had to be home by a certain time. But - well we had a bit more freedom you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Did starting work full time change your relationships with your parents, did they see you any different or did you see them any different?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Well - I sort of - as I got older I sort of - used to think to meself - you know my mum don't have much pleasure, I re
member thinking about that, think, she's always indoors doing something, never see her go out such a wonderful lot, less my dad as I say took her out for the day to the races but - I can't remember and I - I used to think to my self, oh God, fancy being -
 
having a life like that you know, but she was quite contented. You'd never hear her grumble about anything what she done you know, and she used to look after us I mean - we used to have good food and good clothes, she used to look after us - the only thin
g I'd like my dad to have been a bit more - well he was very nice but very quiet sort of man. Never sort of interfered with anything you know. I think she just war the trousers all the time you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Did you still go to Sunday school after you left school?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 
No, I packed all that up, I used to go up the - New Cross, me and my mate, we used to go around - Peckham Rye bandstand, and - get out, and then I - then I remember me and my mother having a battle - when I was about sixteen 'cos I wanted to bu
y me own clothes you see. I didn't like what she used to buy. And she said, all right then, you give me so and so, but - don't forget I want to see something for the money. That you got. 'Cos things was cheap them days, I mean I know me and my friend, we 
used to go right up - High Street, Deptford to buy a new hat of a Saturday or something like that, or a new costume or something like that, well what we was wanting. But - not - not too bad at all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Did you have any change of relationship with your brothers or sisters when you went to work?
