\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Where did you meet her?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Well I - I - got to know her - I don
't know, I think it was a party I got - somewhere - somewhere to a - party, one of the girls at work and I - got to know her and then we - sort of stuck together all the time. And - her mother was partly blind, and they had a house here - just along Queen
s
 Road and her father was a tram driver. I used to go over there quite a lot you know, with 'em when I came home from work I used to go round and call for her or - she used to come and - call for me, and she had a lot of brothers, she was the only girl. Sh
e
 had a lot of - all brothers, but - we used to enjoy ourselves you know. On the quiet. We used to go out and - as I say run round the bandstand with the band playing and - else we used to get up Deptford way of shopping of a weekend when we - when we got 
o
ur money and our mum used to say to us, just mind what you're up to you two, that's what she always used to say, that was - when we go - go out the street door, just mind what you're up to you two, she used to say to us. And then afterwards you see when I
 
went in the picture palace - to work, I sort of - lost touch with her, didn't see much of her any more. She came to my wedding when I was married and - but - didn't see much of her after that. She was supposed to be courting, whether she married this chap
 I don't know. I sort of - you know, we sort of moved a - after we had the children we lived with my mum and - I had two rooms at the top but - afterwards when I went to live with my mother-in-law, we sort of lost touch with her.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Did you bring Dolly back to your house at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 
Oh yes, sometimes, oh yes, she used to come to tea of a Sunday. And my mother used to say, what you two been up to, where did you get to, if I was a bit late you know. My mother never went to bed 'til we was always in, if we
 was out she'd never go to bed 'til she knew that we was in. I - I had to say to her - where have you been to, you're ten minutes late, where have you been to? Oh so and so. Oh I - I've been having a cup of coffee down - cup of cocoa used to be them days.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Can you remember whether your father took any interest in politics when you were a little girl?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 No. No, no I don't know nothing like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 What about your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 No, she never took no interest. They had the evening paper, that's all,
 you know, always had the evening paper to have a read the news but as regards taking they never took no activities in anything like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Do you remember whether they voted in a general election?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Oh voted, oh yes, they always went voting. Yes, they both voted but what they voted for I don't know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Were you ever interested in politics?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 
No. I - you know, I never - you'd die of laughing here, when there's election here they come round they - old Worsley, for Chelsea, you know, he's the MP
 for Chelsea, he come down here, he said, what about voting? I said, oh yes, I'll come. He said, well how are you going to get there? I said, well I'll get someone to push me up in the chair. So he said, that's all right, he said, come in my car. So I sai
d
, all right. I - I'm going to vote, and all the years I've lived here - thirty-three years I've never voted for anybody, and I said to old Worsley, he stood here, he said, come off it, he said to me, I said, yes, listen, do I get any better off? I said, b
l
ooming old Chelsea, I live in can't get bloody helping hand with anything. I said, blow Chelsea, I'm not - blinking Chelsea I said I wish to God I didn't live in it. Then the other bloke come down. What me to take you up, he said. I said, no. I'm not goin
g
 to vote. He said, well - your vote might make all the difference. I said, it might do but I'm not going to. And I've never voted. I don't know if my husband goes and votes, I - 'cos he gets his voting papers but whether he goes I don't know. Do you want 
any more tea?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Do you remember whether anyone outside the house helped your mother look after the home in any way, or the family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 No. No, I don't remember anything like that. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 You can't remember your mother ever being ill?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Oh yes, s
he did have a bad knee once, she fell off a - she was putting a shilling in the meter, and she's about - she was queer, she had a very bad poisoned knee, and had this nurse come in to see her so long, but we had to - you know, she always made - brought us
 
up capable you know, we was all able to - cook a bit of something, she taught us all you know. Well not that - she wasn't a very good cook, my mum, but she wasn't bad you know - we could cook for - she could cook the - she couldn't make nothing fancy like
 we all make today but she could cook like potatoes and greens and meat and anything or - pie or casserole or anything like that but - not fancy cakes and all like that like you know they all make today.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 When this nurse came in would you have to pay her to come in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 
No, I don't think - well I never heard of any money passing over. We never had - I don't suppose I was interested enough to know whether - mother had to pay any money but - I used to get up and - cook the breakfast, or one of us used to
 take it in turns, and then - somebody else used to wash up, all before we went to school, and - you see, so - so we leave mother all right you know before we went to - all tidy, we all had to do our share. Oh yes, she saw -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 That was the only time you can remember her being ill?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 That's the only time. Mm.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 You didn't have any friends or neighbours coming in to help?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 No. NO.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 What about relatives?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Relatives, well - you see we had Aunt Minnie and Aunt Beattie, they used to come 
sometimes, but they never used to do nothing for the old lady.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Can you remember what happened when one of your younger sisters was born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 No, you didn't ask me, no - my young sister Rosie, she's the last one, I don't know, they used to make a job
 of her, whatever for I don't know. But they used to, my mother and father went mad. And she could never be missing, she's a girl - child that you couldn't miss her, you - if she went out she always used to sort of wander, and if they came in, and she - a
n
d sort of looked round us all, find her - they said - we always had to run - as if we had to run to find her you know. It was - always amazed me, 'cos she's the last one you know. But - that's the way it used to go on with her. I don't know why they used 
to say - go and find her, go and bring her in, go and bring her in, wherever she was bring her in, so as they could see her, what the idea was I don't know. 'Cos my mum had fourteen of us, she lost seven.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 You can't remember the actual time when she was being born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 No. No, I can't remember that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Did your parents have many friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Well only neighbours sort of thing, with neighbours you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Where would they see them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Well - the night they went out - they went shopping or they
 might pop in - you know, to see her, something like that you know during the day or sometimes of a evening you know, for a chat but that's about all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Did they have the same friends or did your mother have certain friends and your father have certain friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 No, they were all friends together, all friends together.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Did your father have friends from work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Oh no. No. Not after because my dad finished up for the Borough you see, he was working for the Borough when he was - taken ill.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Were friends ever invited into the house do you remember?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 
Oh yes, they came in, yes, if we had - mum had a - Sunday night mostly you know. She'd have - cut sandwiches and - and they'd bring a drink indoors}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2642704\charrsid1641457  you know, couple of bottle of }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 ale, and then be - we was allowed to stop up 'til about nine o'clock when we were}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2642704\charrsid1641457  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 kids}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2642704\charrsid1641457  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 
and - before nine sometimes say off to bed, off to bed, if they were sitting there having a drink and a sandwich and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Would they came in without an invitation or would they be invited?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 
Well they used to - my mum say well - I'm having - so and so tomorrow night, are you going to call in, and he and - so and so, they just called in you know that was like that sort of thing. When they did in day she was always busy doing he
r housework, because we had a house you see, and we all had to be - bedrooms had to be cleaned and everything else. She never - wasn't much time, she used to go shopping and then - come back, 'cos we used to come home to dinner you see, us - at school, we
 used to come home to dinner every day, and my dad used to come in at twelve, always come in at twelve for dinner, so she had to - sort of put a move on didn't she. But she wasn't too bad at all. Well she always cooked a hot dinner every day for us.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Would your parents ever make music or play games when these people came round?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 
They'd play cards. They'd play - they'd play - all I ever saw - was cards you know. Then as my brother got older he bought a dart - board and they used to - my dad and that 
used to have a go, with him you know and put it in the back yard where there's more room and - and they'd just play a game of darts out there, but that was all I can remember.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 People divide society into different social classes or groups, in that time
 before 1918 do you think of some people belonging to one group or class and some to another?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 
Well - I don't know, they seem - people them days they seemed to be - well I don't know - how you would describe them, they all seemed - very genuine with o
ne another. You know, sort of thing, never - nobody mind what they do for you, sort of help one another sort of thing. But - of course as years gone one - it's been very different now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 But did you think there were different classes of people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Ye
s, 'cos some people were very - some people them days were very rough, you know the - the children and - and poor kids would go to school with no shoes to their feet. I mean we were better off than a lot of kids. I don't know why we were but we were becau
s
e - I mean I've seen kids go to school ragged as hell in my class I can remember - when I've gone to school and they - and I've thought to myself, I said to - gone home and said to my mum, oh so and so didn't have no coat today, or so and so is - she'd sa
y - well - perhaps people.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Can you remember if there were any sort of people that you'd call a real gentleman or a real lady around?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Oh - oh yes, mother - my mother used to work for some people, very well-to-do people in Ivy - Ivydale Road, Nunh
ead, and they were - teachers at school you know and they were very well up and - used to do a lot of charity work they used to, the two sisters used to, and - very nice people, and - we used to go and - there and - go there weekends when - used to make m
y
 mum up a parcel and give it to us to take home and that, I remember used to be pieces of bacon you know and all that, where she used to work, they used to say - to her, Mrs Jordan do you mind having it? It might come in handy. Well my mum always - wanted
 
something for the kids you know, well there was a lot of us to keep, and - we used to go out and collect it on a Saturday, and my sister used to go and - I used to go with her 'cos she used to go step cleaning up there, but that's the people we knew, only
 
- people that - really to say people that got money, you know, the moneyed people, the higher class than what we were. 'Course there's some lovely house - there used to be but I don't know whether its there today, used to be some lovely house in Ivydale R
oad, Nunhead, one time of day years ago. But I expect it's all - that's all altered like now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 What group would you say that you belonged to in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Well, I should say - well the middle I suppose. My mum never seemed to be short of money, i
f we wanted anything it was always got you know, though my dad never used to earn a lot of money, so really - how she - but of course food was very cheap. I mean you could buy six pounds of potatoes for tuppence. - I mean today you've got to pay about eig
ht}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2642704\charrsid1641457  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 pence a - eight }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2642704\charrsid1641457 \endash }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457  eight}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2642704\charrsid1641457  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 
pence a pound. I mean we never got the wages did they in them days. 'Cos I - I know when I was married I only got two pounds seventeen a week. Well that was all my wages was, and - we used to have twelve bob rent we used to pay ou
t of that, and my mum only used to pay seventeen shillings for the house, she said - charged us twelve she's all right where the money was, she was very cute.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 But you've no idea where she got the money from?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 No. No, we never knew. All I - all I 
can remember we were - we were talking the other day, my sister and I over the phone, and I said to her, I wonder where the old lady did get all the money from. So she said, you know when Willie died, that was my mother's brother, he - owed a lot of rate 
money - on the house in Nunhead later he had a big house and he had his own business, well I don't know how \{BLANK\}
 she went away and left him, and - he came and stopped at our house but he died, and he died, whether mother had him insured. But she said, I 
reckon it's where where mum did get the money from. She was saying to me the other day, I reckon - mum got her money out of the insurance money. But then today you could insure your granny, you could insure anybody, but today you can't insure your own peo
ple, you see, all this new law, because when my daughter went to Bexley, how I found out, my husband doesn't believe in insurance, I do, but I think - as I said to him, that's all very well -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Can you remember being brought up to treat people of one gr
oup differently from another group, you said about these teachers - that your mother did the steps for?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Yes. I - well -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Did you have any special attitude towards them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2642704\charrsid1641457 Oh well, you just c}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 reated 'em as you - you know, they were - well - I d
on't know what you'd say about that, I think - all you can say is that - well you knew they was in a different - they were sort of what you'd call moneyed people, they were better off than what we were - you talk - I say, madam or something like that to '
em you know if I talk to 'em, yes madam - so and so and so and so - mother sent me up and all that, that's all you could say.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Were you ever taught to curtsey or anything like that to people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Oh no. No. Nothing of that, no. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 What about the people you said the kids didn't have any shoes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 
Oh yes, well - they were - large families, 'cos you know they had big families them days. And they were just - kids hard - you know, the kids were hard - mothers were hard up I suppose, couldn't afford
 it. That's where I think started - the boots and shoes at the school a shilling a week, I think it was over these children that - my mother always - we used to have our shoes and boots from the - school, but she - she bought everything else.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Did you play with these children when you were at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 
Oh yes. Yes. Didn't make - all together. Yes, you play all together in the playground you know. That's the only time we ever see 'em though - or if we went round there and took a - old coat or anythin
g, couple of frocks or anything like that. That's another thing they don't do today, you don't see \{BLANK\} But they were really rough days for some people.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Can you remember any particular who were very poor?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Well not - no, I can't go back all that far, I can't remember all that far back.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Do you remember any kind of distinction between people who were crafts people in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Who were what?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Any distinction between people who were craftsmen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 No, I - don't remember anything like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Was it possible for people to move from one group into another group?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 
Well if people got on they generally did didn't they, but there wasn't many that got on, it was - very hard going I should imagine them days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Can you remember if you were naughty did your mother ever say, I'll call a policeman?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 
Oh no, was never that. Oh no, nothing like that, no. No, never - you - you knew that if you - no, she never said - my sister-in-law used to say to her kid, here comes the bogey ma
n. But my mother never - she never said anything like that, she'd just give you a wallop and get on with it - else get over it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 You were saying you lived behind a police station at one point?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Before you went to live there did you have any -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Trouble with the police?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Did you come into contact with them or see them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 No. No, nothing of that, no, not when we was -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 How do you think the people looked upon the policemen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Well - I don't - I don't know, the police were
 pretty - quiet sort of thing, you didn't - see all this that goes on today you know with 'em, there's - nothing - I can't remember anything like that going on with 'em you know. Always seemed to be very quiet to me.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 You say your home was rented in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 I think we said about that last time didn't we, that the landlord lived -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 
Just round the corner, mm, from where we lived. He had a - he was a builders bloke you know. And - we had - had a house for seventeen shillings a week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Is this the one in Meeting House Lane?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 
Yes. Mm. Right at the back of the police station, police station used to run - right up, they used to keep all the stray dogs in there you know, and a great big yard for the police, well my husband went 
in - when he came to work at the picture palace when we were married and all that, he - he got to know - they all got - 'cos they used to go in the picture palace - those were so rough houses sometimes in the picture palace in the gallery that he used to 
h
ave to fetch the - have to pay - the old - manager used to have to pay so much for the - coppers - to go in, to keep - order up there. 'Cos it was pretty rough up there sometimes. But other parts of the house was all right, the stalls and the circle and t
hat. But it - it - it's not - it's -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 That was the only job you ever did was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Yes, only - yes, I was with the - I done a - a job at - in Petticoat Lane, right down the bottom there for a few months.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 When was that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Oh, before - before
 I was married, before I went to the picture palace - we used to work down there in - sorting all the tea, tea for the bonded warehouse you know, like a big warehouse in the middle of a - at the bottom end near S}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid2642704\charrsid1641457 a}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 lvation Army, and I used to - my mother use
d to give me my fare to go to work over there and I - me and my mate, we used to spend it - and walk - walk to work. Oh -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 It's a long way though isn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Yes, I should say it was, I know - I should say it was. But -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 What time did you have to set off to get to work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 
Oh seven o'clock in the morning. Yes. Or just after seven, mum'd say, don't forget - don't get spending that money now, you get on the bus. Seventy-eight bus from Mill Street Peckham, it took you right there practically, but -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 What time did you have to start work there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 
Half past eight. And - 'course I used to be always be late, I'm very sorry to say, and the old foreman used to say, where have you been to? And I used to say - couldn't get a bus this morning. In 
them days you could always get a bus not like it is now, you have to wait hours. But me and my mate - mate we used to walk, and of course many a time we got to Tower Bridge, and 'course we've had to wait if the bridge is open, it takes about twenty minute
s
 - them days to open it and let the boats go through and then time it come down, they ring the bell each side all clear - clear, for you to walk over the bridge, and I always used to think you know as a kid, when they used to talk at school about Tower Br
i
dge I always had the idea that when you walked on it you'd fall through the water. It's funny. I - I - I remember going over it and I said - oh - a party of us, I don't know where we were going, but - I remember them taking me and I said, I'm not going on
 
there, I said, 'cos that bridge - bridge is not safe. So they said, what's up with you? I said, no, I said, I couldn't come on there. And they had to really get my confidence before I would go, and I know - that was a long time before I went to work there
 
'cos I wasn't very old, but afterwards I as I say I used to have to get to work that way, but - of course me confidence was restored by then, but I always had an idea that once you walked over there, we - everybody'd fall in the water, it was funny, it re
ally was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Do you remember what kind of hours you had to work in the first job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Oh - oh - well it's eight o'clock in the morning, I didn't get there 'til half past eight - to about half past five, six o'clock.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Did you have any time off for lunch?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 
Oh yes, hour for dinner. Hour for dinner. Then we used to make our own tea of afternoon in this little cubby hole and that. They were happy days they were I tell you. Used to enjoy yourself. I used to get hold of all the boys trousers - and sew 
up the bottoms. Oh used to have some fun. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 
They'd say that Lil again, you wait. So Mr Pepper, that was our manager, he said to me, what will that girl do - it's you again, you will have a game with the boys. I used to have proper - I used to - I
 used to love it you know when I was young, I did, I used to thoroughly enjoy myself. I didn't care a damn about anybody else as long as I enjoyed my - I never used to get in no trouble but - used to enjoy meself in me own way you know, then I always used
 
to have to save the fare to come home, always - we always paid our fare for coming home and - I suppose I think we'd been - after we'd walked in the morning - and spent the dinner money and all, we spend the money - at dinner time we'd have no dinner. We'
d have a - a couple o}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2642704\charrsid1641457 f }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 
rolls or something and then one of the girls says to Jessie one day that - we'd - she'd go and buy some dinner and we paid her so much. So after a little while we used to have a good inner like stew or - or so much towards sausages or
 something like that and then she used to cook the bit of dinner in the - in the little me}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2642704\charrsid1641457 s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 
s room, we had a little mess room and - and then - we used to always save the fare for going home of a night time, and of a morning my mother used to say - come on,}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2642704\charrsid1641457  come on, there's no moc}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 
king about, when she called you just had to get out of it whether you wanted to or not. And - come on, you'll never get to work, and - I'd say, well - I've got to - hurry up now, you'll never catch that bus. Then I'd meet my mate, my
 friend, say well what about going? And she'd say - well - we've got so and so time, we'll walk. We used to walk all the distance. And it's quite a step you know, right up to Middlesex Street, and you know afterwards - later years before I ever got like t
h
is, I used to go down that - Middlesex Street all on me own of Sundays, put my dinner in here, he used to be out - with the boy, my boy was in the - my youngest one was in the - not the Home Guard - Cadets, at the - And he used to go out of a morning, he 
used to have to go on parade or duty, I used to do all the dinner, and I used to go - go in hours down - buy shopping and stuff down - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2642704\charrsid1641457 Petticoat}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457  Lane. 'Cos it was quite interesting down there weekends you know. Oh all lots of bits down there. Mm. I used to 
get back here about one o'clock. But it was just the fun that I used to like to go out. I suppose going to work all the week - I didn't like stopping in Sundays, I'd get up and do - early, get on me work and - and - 'course sometimes me old man used to go
 
to work Sunday morning if there was anything special on, and he'd go so would - nobody here so I used to - sling meself out and get back here about one o'clock, just pop me dinner on a low gas, get it ready by two. Time he was ready to come in. So - but w
e -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Did you work Saturday mornings in this first job you did?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Yes. Mmm, oh yes, we'd always work - barring when he went in the Civil Service 'cos they don't do no work on a Saturday.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 I was thinking of your job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Oh. Oh. No, no, not Sat
urday, never went Saturday. No, I used to have the job at home of doing the parlour out of a Sunday - a Saturday morning while mum went shopping see. I always had to do the - parlour out, we always called it the parlour them days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 How long did you do this job in Petticoat Lane for?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Ay? Oh - not a - not a great length - not a great - not a great lot.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11756613 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Were you sorry to leave it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6241478 LE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 Mm, I was really sorry because - a happy little job. I got the more - I'd go we used to do the - do the packet
s of tea, the quarters of tea, and the harried beans }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2642704\charrsid1641457 \endash }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457  pick}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2642704\charrsid1641457 
 \lquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3736647\charrsid1641457 
em all out and put 'em - weight 'em up into pounds you know, and - all - all stuff - like rice and - stuff like that, you wouldn't believe how - mice get in them bags would you. They do you know.
 They breed and all in them bags of - I never - eat anything like that, it's like pickles. I've seen pickles done, I went - only was th}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2642704\charrsid1641457 e}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
